{{c1::flū́men, flū́minis}} has gender {{c2::n}} and means {{c3::river}} with English derivatives {{c1::flume, fluminous, cf. fluō}}

{{c1::génus, géneris}} has gender {{c2::n}} and means {{c3::origin; kind type, sort, class}} with English derivatives {{c1::genus, generic, genitive, gender, general, generous, genuine, degenerate, genre, congenial}}
{{c1::hóstis, hóstis (sg)}} has gender {{c2::m}} and means {{c3::an enemy (of the state)}} with English derivatives {{c1::hostile, hostility, host}}
{{c1::hóstēs, hóstium (pl)}} has gender {{c2::m}} and means {{c3::the enemy}} with English derivatives {{c1::hostile, hostility, host}}

{{c1::lū́dus, lū́dī}} has gender {{c2::m}} and means {{c3::game, sport; school}} with English derivatives {{c1::ludicrous, delude, elude, elusive, allude, allusion, illusion, collusion, interlude, prelude, postlude}}
{{c1::próbitās, probitā́tis}} has gender {{c2::f}} and means {{c3::uprightness, honesty}} with English derivatives {{c1::probity, probation}}
{{c1::sciéntia, sciéntiae}} has gender {{c2::f}} and means {{c3::knowledge}} with English derivatives {{c1::science, scientific, scientist, prescience; cf. scīre, to know}}

{{c1::clā́rus, clā́ra, clā́rum}} means {{c3::clear, bright; renowned, famous, illustrious}} with English derivatives {{c1::clarify, clarity, claret, clarinet, clarion, declare, Clara, Clarissa, Claribel}}
{{c1::mortā́lis, mortā́le}} means {{c3::mortal}} with English derivatives {{c1::mortality, immortal, immortality; cf. mors}}
{{c1::cūr}} is a/an {{c4::adv}} and means {{c3::why}}
{{c1::deínde}} is a/an {{c4::adv}} and means {{c3::thereupon, next, then}}
{{c1::flúō, flúere, flū́xī, flū́xum}} means {{c3::to flow}} with English derivatives {{c1::fluid, fluent, flux, influx, affluence, influence, confluence, influenza, flu, mellifluous, superfluous}}

{{c1::légō, légere, lḗgī, lḗctum}} means {{c3::to pick out, choose; read}} with English derivatives {{c1::elect, elegant, eligible, lecture, legend, legible, intellect; cf. dīligō, intellegō, neglegō}}
{{c1::mísceō, miscḗre, míscuī, míxtum}} means {{c3::to mix, stir up, disturb}} with English derivatives {{c1::miscellaneous, miscible, meddle, medley, melee, promiscuous}}
{{c1::móveō, movḗre, mṓvī, mṓtum}} means {{c3::to move; arouse, affect}} with English derivatives {{c1::mobile, motion, motive, motor, commotion, emotion, remote, locomotive, mutiny}}
{{c1::vídeor, vidḗrī, vī́sus sum}} means {{c3::passive of videō, to be seen, seem, appear}}
